# pixi-lock-rebase-regenerate — History

## v1.8.0 (2026-05-17)

**Changed by:** ProjectAgamemnon PRs #390 (root `pixi.lock`) and #391 (`clients/python/pixi.lock`), 2026-05-17
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Added new "When to Use" trigger (13) covering pixi-binary-version skew between developer
  and CI causing lockfile-format rejection (distinct from SHA-mismatch / Phase 3f)
- Added new Phase 3g section: **"Pixi Binary Version Skew Causing Lock-Format Drift"**
  with copy-paste workflow (find CI's pinned `pixi-version:`, install locally to per-shell
  dir, delete + regenerate lock, push)
- Explicitly contrasted Phase 3f (SHA-mismatch, 1-line diff) vs Phase 3g (format drift,
  potentially structural diff) — both fix shapes look similar but have different diagnostic
  signals
- Added 2 new Failed Attempts rows:
  - `pixi install --frozen` locally giving false-green signal (local newer pixi reads its
    own lock format fine; does NOT prove CI compatibility)
  - Considered bumping CI's pinned `pixi-version:` but rejected (cascades ecosystem-wide)
- Added new `pixi-version-skew` and `lock-format-drift` tags
- Added Verified On row for ProjectAgamemnon PRs #390/#391

### Why

Previous v1.7.0 documented the SHA-mismatch case (Phase 3f) and even mentioned "newer pixi
may write fields that older pixi versions reject" in passing — but only as a sub-bullet
inside Phase 3f. ProjectAgamemnon hit the format-drift case twice on 2026-05-17 (PR #390
and PR #391) with developer running v0.67.2 against CI's v0.39.5. The pattern is distinct
enough from a SHA-mismatch (different diagnostic signals, different failure messages,
different diff shape) that it warrants its own phase rather than a sub-bullet.

Critically, the v1.7.0 guidance assumed the agent would discover the format-drift case
while diagnosing a SHA-mismatch. In practice, agents reach for `pixi install --frozen`
locally as a smoke test, see it pass, and conclude the fix is correct — only to have CI
fail again with the same format error. The new Phase 3g calls this out explicitly and
provides a per-shell pixi installation recipe that reproduces the CI failure locally.

