## v1.7.0 (2026-05-11)

**Changed by:** ProjectAgamemnon PR #368 (2026-05-11 ecosystem-wide easy-issue sweep)
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Added new "When to Use" trigger covering comment-only / metadata-only manifest edits that
  invalidate the local-package SHA256 in `pixi.lock`
- Added new Phase 3f section: **"Use `pixi install` NOT `pixi update` for SHA-only fixes"**
  with copy-paste workflow that pins the CI's pixi version
- Added 1 new Failed Attempts row documenting `pixi update` over-broadening the diff
  from 1 line to ~50 lines on a comment-only manifest edit
- Cross-referenced the existing `feedback_pixi_lock_version_pin` user-memory note (use CI's
  pinned pixi version when regenerating, not the latest)
- Updated Verified On with ProjectAgamemnon PR #368 (issue #104)

### Why

Previous versions (v1.0.0–v1.6.0) all instructed agents to "run `pixi install`" without
explaining what would happen if an agent reached for `pixi update` instead. In the
2026-05-11 ecosystem sweep, a fix-wave agent on ProjectAgamemnon PR #368 first tried
`pixi update --manifest-path clients/python/pixi.toml` for what was actually a comment-only
edit to `clients/python/pyproject.toml`. `pixi update` re-resolved the dependency graph
against the latest available versions and produced ~50 lines of unrelated diff (ruff, mypy,
transitive bumps), risking unrelated breakage. Reverting and using `pixi install` produced
the expected 1-line SHA fix.

The distinction matters because the two commands look interchangeable at a glance but have
fundamentally different scopes:

- `pixi install` — reproduces the lockfile to satisfy the current manifest; if package
  versions haven't moved, only the affected SHA changes
- `pixi update` — re-resolves against the latest available versions, regardless of what
  changed in the manifest

For comment-only or metadata-only manifest edits, the difference is dramatic.

