## v1.6.0 (2026-05-07)

**Changed by:** ProjectHermes 31-PR rebase swarm session — discovered main itself can be the broken party
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Added 3 new "Use when" trigger conditions covering main-itself-is-broken detection
- Added new "Detection: Is It Main or Is It the Branch?" section with 4-step diagnostic + hotfix flow
- Added 2 Failed Attempts rows documenting wasted per-branch fixup work
- Added Quick Diagnostic single-command snippet
- Updated Verified On table with ProjectHermes #593 → #599 case

### Why

The previous version (v1.5.0) covered branch-side staleness (rebase conflicts, Dependabot
fast-fails, post-version-bump). It didn't cover the case where **main itself** ships a
stale pixi.lock — a PR with `[project.dependencies]` changes that didn't regenerate the
lock during merge. The local-package `sha256:` in pixi.lock changes whenever pyproject.toml
contributes to the package's source-tree hash; if that SHA doesn't match, `pixi install
--locked` fails everywhere — main and every PR rebased onto it.

Our session wasted ~10 minutes spawning a per-branch fixup wave (4 parallel agents,
12 PRs touched) before noticing every branch's CI was still red. The fix was a 1-line
hotfix PR on main; afterward every branch needed ANOTHER rebase to inherit the fix.
The new "Detection: Is It Main or Is It the Branch?" section short-circuits this
investigation.

### Previous version (v1.5.0) snapshot

